# Fluff Date: 2026-02-24 13:31:06
<overview>
<p>The Capital Drone represents the Star League's most ambitious application of autonomous warfare technology to naval combat. Developed as the cornerstone of the Space Defense System, these unmanned warships were designed to protect critical Terran Hegemony worlds without requiring the human crews that represented the most precious and irreplaceable resource in the Star League Navy. Operating entirely under machine control, drone warships could engage hostile forces with a precision unconstrained by the limitations of human reaction time or the vulnerabilities of organic crews.</p><p>The program encompassed multiple hull configurations adapted from existing warship designs, with the primary production model achieving a remarkable combination of destroyer-class mobility and battleship-grade firepower that made it one of the most feared weapons platforms of the Star League era. Though the Capital Drone achieved considerable technical success, the autonomous nature of these vessels would prove both their greatest strength and their most troubling legacy, as the loss of centralized control during the fall of the Star League left functioning drones as unpredictable hazards across the former Hegemony.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The primary M-5 production model employs a heavily modified Lola II destroyer hull, retaining the original frame's thrust characteristics while mounting offensive armament nearly equal to a Texas-class battleship despite displacing barely more than half the tonnage. Eighteen naval lasers provide layered defense across all firing arcs, while paired heavy naval particle projection cannons in the nose enable devastating slashing attacks from beyond an opponent's effective engagement range. Naval autocannons in both medium and heavy calibers deliver sustained broadside firepower, and capital missile launchers including AR-10 systems provide flexible anti-ship capability at all ranges. The drone's massive heat sink array allows it to fire both autocannon broadsides simultaneously without risk of overheating.</p><p>The autonomous control systems replace the hundreds of crew members typically required aboard a warship of this displacement, eliminating all life support, quarters, and personnel-related systems to free tonnage for additional weapons and ammunition. An integrated SDS Drone Control System manages all combat functions at performance levels of a trained warship crew. The SDS Self-Destruct System prevents capture, though its placement in the engine compartment creates a critical vulnerability where a fortunate hit to the aft section can trigger premature detonation. The M-5C command variant adds an Autonomous Tactical Analysis Computer capable of coordinating up to fifty other SDS drones, creating networked defensive formations of extraordinary tactical flexibility. Ferro-carbide armor provides substantial protection relative to the hull's displacement.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The M-5C command variant served as the tactical brain of SDS defensive formations, its Autonomous Tactical Analysis Computer processing millions of combat simulations per second and relaying optimized attack solutions to all connected drones. Each SDS network node included one or more M-5C coordinators directing formations of standard M-5 drones and lighter M-3 DropShip-class platforms. To accommodate the massive ATAC computer array, the M-5C downgraded its own drone control computer, reducing individual accuracy but compensating through networked targeting assistance from subordinate units. Two additional heavy naval particle projection cannons enhanced the command variant's bow armament. The loss of an M-5C coordinator significantly degraded the combat effectiveness of its entire drone formation, making these command units priority targets during the Liberation of Terra.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Capital Drone program evolved from the Star League's broader Space Defense System initiative, which sought to create an automated defensive network capable of protecting the Terran Hegemony's most critical worlds without straining the navy's finite supply of trained crews. The earliest experiments began with the M-1 drone, a modified Ares Mark VII attack craft that demonstrated the basic viability of autonomous combat operations when it entered trials in 2692. The M-2 followed, adapting Hector DropShip hulls to drone control, before the M-3 scaled the concept to Pentagon-class assault DropShip frames and entered widespread production from 2698. Each iteration refined the autonomous control systems and combat protocols that would eventually enable capital-ship-class operations.</p><p>The M-4 proof-of-concept program converted ten Baron-class destroyer hulls to validate drone control at the capital warship scale, while the more ambitious M-6 program attempted to adapt the Texas-class battleship hull but proved infeasible. The breakthrough came with the M-5, which entered production in 2710 at Nicholas Spacecraft and Ulsop Robotics facilities on New Earth. Built on modified Lola II destroyer hulls, the M-5 achieved the program's ultimate goal: a fully autonomous capital warship capable of engaging and destroying crewed vessels of comparable or greater displacement. The design mounted firepower approaching that of a Texas-class battleship while maintaining destroyer-class acceleration, creating a platform that conventional warships found extraordinarily difficult to counter.</p><p>The M-5C command variant added the Autonomous Tactical Analysis Computer, enabling a single drone to coordinate the actions of up to fifty subordinate units. This networking capability transformed individual drone warships into integrated defensive formations of devastating effectiveness. The SDS network functioned as intended during the Star League era, its mere existence deterring aggression against Hegemony worlds.</p><p>When Stefan Amaris launched his coup against First Lord Richard Cameron, the SDS became a weapon turned against its creators. Amaris forces seized control of the drone network, and the Caspar drones that had been built to protect the Hegemony instead fought to defend the usurper's conquest. During the Liberation of Terra, General Kerensky's SLDF forces were forced to fight through dense formations of the very drones their government had commissioned, suffering devastating losses in the process. Only after Kerensky's technicians devised a jamming system to disrupt the drones' coordination network could the SLDF forces overcome the automated defenders. Without the jamming breakthrough, the Caspar formations defending Terra might have proven insurmountable.</p><p>The fall of the Star League effectively ended the Capital Drone as an operational system. Surviving drones lacking central coordination reverted to basic autonomous protocols, becoming unpredictable hazards in former Hegemony space. The Word of Blake would later resurrect the concept during the Jihad, developing the Caspar II program that applied updated drone technology to new hull designs, demonstrating that the fundamental principles behind the Capital Drone remained viable centuries after their original implementation.</p>
</history>

